<published>2005-08-02T22:08:36-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=438&amp;p=3411#p3411</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=438&amp;p=3411#p3411"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[DumbNES]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=438&amp;p=3411#p3411"><![CDATA[
Yay:<br />cart PCB's arrived today, and look awesome.<br />I soldered two up and can program the CPLD fine, but...<br /><br />Boo:<br />devkit PCB's aren't here yet<br />eprom programmer isn't here yet<br /><br />so... I can't program the flash on the damn things to test out the rest of the board or the mapper<br /><br />Additional Boo:<br />Benchmarq parts are way, way too tall to fit in the case (sram with internal battery and watchdog ic).  Dallas / ST parts are just as tall, but Simtek parts will work, if I can find a place that will sell them in onesies (and when I do find them, I have 2x 32 KB and 1x 128 KB Benchmarq parts for sale at cost).<br /><br />usb link cable isn't talking to the host pc yet (should have gone with a ftdi+pic combo (it just works), the usb pics are nasty)<br /><br />Note:<br />This isn't designed as a console copier.  It can act as one for what, half of released games or so, but it's designed primarily as a development tool.  I orignally planned on designing the same PCB, and seperate fusemaps for each of the discrete mappers, so people could get a UOROM dev cart, or a Color Dreams dev cart, etc..., but after designing that and writing the vhdl, with a superset of pins needed for any one design, I realized that the other mappers would all fit together, so I didn't have to have 10 seperate mapper loads, just the one.<br /><br />It's also a 'first step', since I really want to design a MMC5-esque devcart with exwram graphics and math copro (mult, div, table-basd trig) etc..., but I didn't feel comfortable going whole hog and designing a fpga-based board with the regulators to provide the core voltages, level converters on 60 pins of i/o, etc...  Instead, I started with the simplest, cheapest 5V CPLD I knew of and grew from there, seeing what would fit.  I ended up doubling to a 64, which let get get MMC1 in and a nicer control mechanism for native mode, but going any larger would be really expensive.<br /><br />No IRQ counter because I didn't have a spare pin or macrocells.  One could be added at the expense of say, CHR banking by grounding CHR A16, grabbing the CHR A16 line off the mapper and soldering a jumper to the IRQ pin on the edge connector, and removing all the CHR banking code (close to half the macrocells actually, and replacing them with a latchable counter).  Aren't CPLDs wonderful <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br />If you kept the MMC1 style PRG and config mode code, you could then create a shall we call it MMC1.5, with a M2 IRQ counter (PPU_A12 is a bit trickier, but doable, as you need to cut the A12 into mapper trace and stick a filtering cap on the input), 16/16 banked/switched PRG, and VRAM.  Stick the latch on CHR reg 0, and the enable/acknowledge/reload logic on CHR reg 1.<p>Statistics: Posted by Guest — Tue Aug 02, 2005 10:08 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
